HB 2685 Text skip navigation SENATE PRESIDENT SENATORS COMMITTEES VIDEO/AUDIO DISTRICT MAPS SENATE CLERK SENATE RULES HOUSE SPEAKER DELEGATES COMMITTEES VIDEO/AUDIO DISTRICT MAPS HOUSE CLERK HOUSE RULES HOUSE STAFF JOINT INTERIM COMMITTEES LEGISLATIVE ADMINISTRATOR LEGISLATIVE SERVICES DIVISION PUBLIC INFORMATION LEGISLATIVE AUTOMATED SYSTEMS DIVISION LEGISLATIVE AUDITOR'S OFFICE PERFORMANCE EVALUATION & RESEARCH DIVISION POST AUDIT DIVISION BUDGET DIVISION REGULATORY AND FISCAL AFFAIRS DIVISION CLAIMS COMMISSION CRIME VICTIMS RULE-MAKING REVIEW SPECIAL INVESTIGATIONS JUDICIAL COMP. COMMISSION JOINT RULES STAFF INFO BILL STATUS BILL STATUS BILL TRACKING STATE LAW WEST VIRGINIA CODE ACTS OF THE LEGISLATURE CODE OF 1931 WV CONSTITUTION US CONSTITUTION REPORTS AGENCY REPORTS AGENCY GRANT AWARDS PERFORMANCE EVALUATIONS POST AUDITS EDUCATIONAL CITIZEN’S GUIDE INTERNSHIP PROGRAM PAGE PROGRAM PUBLICATIONS PHOTO GALLERY CAPITOL HISTORY HOW A BILL BECOMES LAW CONTACT SENATE ROSTER HOUSE ROSTER PUBLIC INFO. NEWS RELEASES HELPFUL LINKS Introduced Version House Bill 2685 History |  Email Key: Green = existing Code. Red = new code to be enacted WEST VIRGINIA LEGISLATURE2025 REGULAR SESSIONIntroducedHouse Bill 2685By Delegate Pritt[Introduced February 20, 2025; referred to the Committee on the Judiciary]A BILL to amend the Code of West Virginia, 1931, as amended, by adding a new section, designated §7-14-13a, relating to providing county sheriffs the authority to appoint a deputy chief; creating requirements for the establishment of the position; establishing duties; making the appointment of the position discretionary; and requiring a department to have at least 25 deputy sheriffs to be eligible to utilize position.  Be it enacted by the Legislature of West Virginia: ARTICLE 14. CIVIL SERVICE FOR DEPUTY SHERIFFS. §7-14-13a.  Appointment of deputy chief to county sheriff's department. (a) County sheriffs shall have the authority and discretion to appoint a qualified person to the position of deputy chief.  The deputy chief will serve as an augmentation to the sheriff and chief deputy, as well as fulfill statutory requirements of a sheriff’s department.  (b) The deputy chief position would operate the same as the chief deputy, but would be one step below the chief deputy in the scope of authority. The deputy chief would be in place to augment the appointed administrative staff, but would also be subject to work assignments the same as sworn deputy sheriffs when need be. (c) The filling and use of this position would be entirely at the discretion of the sheriff of the county. Eligible sheriffs are under no obligation to utilize this position, but may do so if they feel that the position would be of benefit to the agency and the county they serve.(d) County sheriffs may appoint a deputy chief if the department has 25 or more sworn deputy sheriffs on staff.(e) The deputy chief position would be subject to the same laws and rules sets as the chief deputy, including all state statutes and the federal Hatch Act. NOTE: The purpose of this bill is to provide for the position of deputy chief, to establish duties of the position; to make the appointment of the position discretionary; and to require department have at least 25 deputy sheriffs to be eligible to utilize position. Strike-throughs indicate language that would be stricken from a heading or the present law and underscoring indicates new language that would be added. Bill Status  | Bill Tracking  | Legacy WV Code  | Bulletin Board  | District Maps  | Senate Roster  | House Roster  | Live  | Blog  | Jobs  | Links  | Home This Web site is maintained by the West Virginia Legislature's Office of Reference & Information.  | Terms of Use | Webmaster | © 2025 West Virginia Legislature ** Print On Demand Name: Email: Phone:


